questiontext.text:
The image below shows a model for viscoelastic materials, combining two springs and a dashpot as shown.


Where $$F$$ is a fixed load applied to the system, $$u$$ is the displacement of the system, and $$\dot{u}$$ is the rate of displacement of the system, with respect to time.


A fixed load (F) is instantaneously applied, and later instantaneously removed, as shown in the graph below.



From the options below, select which graph correctly represents the displacement/time plot that would be obtained in this situation.

{1:MCV:~


#Incorrect~=


#Good Job!~


#Incorrect~


#Incorrect}

generalfeedback.text:
The correct answer is shown in the image above.

The initial instantaneous displacement when the load is applied (and later removed) is governed by the two spring constants, and is defined by the equation
$$\frac{F}{\left(K_1+K_2\right)}$$

The equilibrium displacment is equal to
$$\frac{F}{\left(K_2\right)}$$
as it is this spring which is carrying the whole load at equilibrium.

The curve between inbetween initial and equilibrium displacements is determined by a combination of the two spring constants, and the viscosity of the dashpot.

hint.text:
HINT

Think about how the system will responed initially, and whether or not it will reach equilibrium.

The equilibrium displacment is equal to
$$\frac{F}{\left(K_2\right)}$$
as it is this spring which is carrying the whole load at equilibrium.

The curve between inbetween initial and equilibrium displacements is determined by a combination of the two spring constants, and the viscosity of the dashpot.
